learned and the challenges that
remain.

11:17.176 --> 11:21.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The outbreak
first began
in Eastern Guinea back in
December of 2013

11:21.881 --> 11:26.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and then spread to neighboring
Liberia and
Sierra Leone. More than 2,500
people died

11:26.786 --> 11:31.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Guinea before it was fully
contained. And,
today, an estimated 6,000
children there are

11:31.991 --> 11:34.227 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
orphans because of the epidemic.

11:34.260 --> 11:38.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's now been six weeks
since the last
known Ebola patient repeatedly
tested negative

11:38.197 --> 11:43.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the virus. Reports from
Guinea today suggest
a mix of both celebration and
wariness.

11:43.903 --> 11:47.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sheri Fink has chronicled the
impact of the
epidemic for The New York Times,
and was part

11:47.774 --> 11:50.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the team who won the Pulitzer
Prize for
its coverage.

11:50.743 --> 11:56.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Sheri Fink, Guinea says no
more Ebola.
Tell us, how big a deal is this?

11:56.916 --> 12:00.253 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHERI FINK, The New York Times:
It's a big
deal.

12:00.286 --> 12:05.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you have said, it's been two
years since
experts believe that that first
case in a

12:05.291 --> 12:11.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
little village in Guinea started
this epidemic.
That's a very long time. And
today marks the

12:11.864 --> 12:16.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
date that all three of those
most affected
countries have broken that
original chain

12:17.003 --> 12:21.975 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of transmission, that
human-to-human transmission
that has led us to this day,
with thousands

12:22.008 --> 12:26.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of deaths and many, many
thousands of people
getting sick with Ebola.

12:26.245 --> 12:31.651 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Is the
scientific community
pretty confident that we are in
fact at zero?

12:31.684 --> 12:37.190 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Liberia at one point was
declared Ebola-free,
and then some new cases erupted.
So how confident

12:37.223 --> 12:39.726 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can we be that this really is
it?

12:39.759 --> 12:44.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHERI FINK: So, this has been
something that
we have learned this year.

12:44.063 --> 12:49.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, people might even be
surprised Ebola
has slipped from the headlines,
that the transmissions

12:49.769 --> 12:55.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
continued to go up until this
date. And that
is because there have been sort
of these cases

12:55.475 --> 13:01.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that nobody knew about of
potential Ebola
kind of hanging out in certain
parts of the

13:01.848 --> 13:08.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
body that are immunologically
protected and
reemerging in some survivors,
causing these

13:08.554 --> 13:10.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
little mini-outbreaks.

13:10.456 --> 13:16.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, indeed, Liberia reached this
milestone
a few months ago and twice has
had small flare-ups

13:16.429 --> 13:21.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that are thought to be linked to
transmission
from survivors in very rare
cases thought

13:21.868 --> 13:24.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be sexually transmitted, for
one thing.

13:24.637 --> 13:30.176 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So now the World Health
Organization is saying,
OK, human-to-human transmission
has stopped,

13:30.209 --> 13:35.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but Guinea will enter a 90-day
period of what
they're calling enhanced
surveillance to be

13:35.648 --> 13:41.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really on the lookout for
occasional sporadic
cases that could pop up and lead
to more cases.

13:41.854 --> 13:46.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Your reporting
over the
last months and year have
revealed that there

13:46.592 --> 13:50.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are some real problems with the
way the World
Health Organization responded to
this epidemic.

13:50.763 --> 13:54.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Can you tell us about some of
those -- some
of the problems that they had,
and how have

13:54.500 --> 13:56.469 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they been addressed?

13:56.502 --> 14:02.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERI FINK: Well, the World
Health Organization
has really been a punching bag
for this outbreak.

14:02.442 --> 14:05.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it should be said that
nobody responded
very well at the beginning.

14:05.978 --> 14:11.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, certainly, the World Health
Organization,
as that U.N. body that's in
charge of the

14:11.117 --> 14:16.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
world's health, came in for a
lot of criticism,
and they said it was justified.
And numerous

14:16.522 --> 14:21.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
groups have come out, experts,
trying to say,
what can we learn from this?

14:21.260 --> 14:27.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The essential fact was, early in
the outbreak,
the WHO failed to sort of
understand its gravity.

14:27.767 --> 14:32.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, these cases popped up in
a part of
the world that hadn't been known
really to

14:32.605 --> 14:37.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have Ebola outbreaks in the
past, right at
the border of three countries,
and very quickly

14:37.944 --> 14:41.147 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
had hit capital cities.

14:41.180 --> 14:47.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there wasn't just enough of a
sense of
urgency in that very early
response, a sense

14:47.420 --> 14:52.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that this was different from the
WHO. Plus,
they had cut down their outbreak
response

14:52.525 --> 14:58.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
units just before the outbreak
happened. This
was because, you know, they
hadn't had as

14:58.164 --> 15:04.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
much money to work with, with
the global financial
crisis, and so they chose to cut
certain aspects

15:04.237 --> 15:06.272 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of their global health
portfolio.

15:06.305 --> 15:11.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Unfortunately, one of them was
outbreak response.
So now the focus is how to
strengthen that

15:11.477 --> 15:13.246 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the future.

15:13.279 --> 15:16.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You reported
also that,
sometimes, political concerns
got in the way

15:16.849 --> 15:20.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of public health concerns.
Explain how that
happens.

15:20.553 --> 15:25.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHERI FINK: So, the WHO is made
up of its
member countries.

15:25.892 --> 15:30.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in the past, even with this
outbreak,
we saw that there is sort of a
punitive response

15:30.530 --> 15:36.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when a country has a dangerous
disease like
Ebola within its borders.
Airlines shut down

15:37.003 --> 15:42.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
flights, countries pull out, and
the thought
is also that these countries put
pressure

15:42.975 --> 15:46.312 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the local -- the regional WHO
offices.

15:46.345 --> 15:51.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They don't want a big deal to be
made of this
outbreak. So, looking forward, a
lot of these

15:51.350 --> 15:56.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
groups are saying the WHO needs
to be protected
from that political pressure, so
that they

15:56.823 --> 16:02.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can address an outbreak, not
minimize it,
in the beginning, as well as the
other countries

16:02.762 --> 16:07.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the world need to reward
countries that
are willing to come forward and
say, we have

16:07.767 --> 16:09.669 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
got an outbreak.

16:09.702 --> 16:15.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that reward is, you know,
immediate assistance
to fight the outbreak. More
broadly, health

16:15.942 --> 16:19.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
systems really need to be
strengthened in
all these countries. These are
countries with

16:19.946 --> 16:24.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
poor health systems to begin
with, and all
the countries of the world have
realized that

16:24.684 --> 16:27.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
there is an interest in
strengthening those
health systems.

16:27.720 --> 16:34.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, that's partly to help
people, humanitarian,
but partly so that future
outbreaks of even

16:34.660 --> 16:39.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more dangerous, you know,
epidemics would
be stopped at their source.

16:39.198 --> 16:42.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Sheri Fink of
The New York Times, thank you so
much.

16:42.335 --> 16:44.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SHERI FINK: Thanks.

16:44.237 --> 16:48.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Clearly, the best
way to stop
Ebola altogether would be
developing a vaccine.

16:48.875 --> 16:53.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in fact, more than a dozen
trials and
experiments are under way.

16:53.246 --> 16:57.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Earlier this year, our science
correspondent,
Miles O'Brien, reported on some
of those efforts

16:57.216 --> 17:01.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in West Africa and why the
search for a cure
has been so difficult.

17:01.854 --> 17:06.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is an encore look from his
series Cracking
Ebola's Code.

17:06.459 --> 17:13.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It's dark and
early in Freetown,
Sierra Leone. A team of
pharmacists is in

17:13.399 --> 17:18.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
a nondescript government
building preparing
the day's supply of an
experimental vaccine

17:19.005 --> 17:22.275 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
against Ebola.

17:22.308 --> 17:34.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The clock starts running when
they take the
vaccine out of a very deep
freeze. This is

17:34.720 --> 17:40.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
likely the coldest spot in the
whole country.
The vaccine can only be thawed
out right before

17:40.226 --> 17:46.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it is injected, or it will lose
its potency,
and all of this will be a waste
of time, money

17:46.499 --> 17:48.134 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and hope.

17:48.167 --> 17:54.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, right now, timing and
temperature are
absolutely critical. And then it
happens.

17:54.707 --> 17:59.478 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOMAN: The power went out.

17:59.512 --> 18:05.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Another reminder
of how hard
it is to conduct a high-tech
vaccine trial

18:05.985 --> 18:14.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in one of the poorest countries
on the planet.
But they are ready. They have
got two backup

18:14.327 --> 18:19.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
generators for the building,
solar-charged
batteries, and, if all else
fails, a special

18:19.932 --> 18:25.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
container that maintains about
100 degrees
below zero Fahrenheit for five
days without

18:25.638 --> 18:29.275 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
power.

18:29.308 --> 18:35.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pharmacist Morrison Jusu is
delivering the
vaccine three-and-a-half miles
across Freetown.

18:35.414 --> 18:41.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After a seemingly endless
national nightmare,
he carries a cooler full of
expectations.

18:41.387 --> 18:43.522 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He knows much is riding with
him.

18:43.556 --> 18:49.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MORRISON JUSU, Pharmacist: Some
people lost
family members. And some
families were essentially

18:49.095 --> 18:58.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wiped out as a result of this
thing. And if
this vaccine proves out to be
something that

18:58.137 --> 19:06.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prevents such in the future,
then it's -- it's
-- words cannot describe how
much relief that

19:06.479 --> 19:08.581 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
would be to this community.

19:08.614 --> 19:15.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: While Jusu and
the vaccine
are wending their way, a line is
growing outside

19:15.054 --> 19:18.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
their destination, Freetown's
Connaught Hospital.

19:18.758 --> 19:23.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The volunteers start showing up
before dawn.
They are health care workers.
This trial is

19:23.896 --> 19:29.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
limited to them because they
are, by far,
the most at risk of contracting
Ebola virus

19:29.702 --> 19:34.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
disease. Even though there is no
evidence
the vaccine poses any real
danger, they must

19:34.807 --> 19:36.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
weigh the rumors and the
uncertainties.

19:36.876 --> 19:41.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMED SAMBOLA, Vaccine Trial
Volunteer (through
translator): Life is all about
risks. But

19:41.247 --> 19:43.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I believe it will be of help in
the job that
I do.

19:43.482 --> 19:46.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RUGIATU CONTEH, Vaccine Trial
Volunteer (through
translator): It is a high risk
for me. I believe

19:47.019 --> 19:50.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this can protect me from Ebola,
and that's
why I came here for this
vaccine.

19:50.456 --> 19:55.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It wasn't always
this way.
The trial got off to a slow
start when it

19:55.628 --> 19:58.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
began in April. People were too
afraid.

19:58.464 --> 20:01.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Dr. Mohamed Samai is one of the
principal
investigators.

20:01.367 --> 20:03.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. MOHAMED SAMAI, Provost,
College of Medicine
and Allied Health Sciences:
People said the

20:03.536 --> 20:10.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
vaccine was the Ebola virus, so,
once you
get it, you become infected. So,
a lot of

20:10.443 --> 20:16.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people were not willing to come
forward there
in the first week to take the
vaccine, because

20:16.382 --> 20:19.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they thought they should wait
and see what
happens.

20:19.118 --> 20:24.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The vaccine does
contain a
piece of the Ebola virus, a
protein. It's

20:24.457 --> 20:29.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enough to trick the body into
triggering its
natural defenses, but won't give
the recipient

20:29.628 --> 20:32.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Ebola virus disease.

20:32.064 --> 20:36.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the wall in the lobby of the
hospital,
a spontaneous memorial to some
of the doctors

20:36.769 --> 20:43.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and nurses who died here during
the epidemic,
a grim reminder of what
motivates volunteers

20:43.142 --> 20:44.944 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
like Richard Kanu.

20:44.977 --> 20:47.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD KANU, Vaccine Trial
Volunteer (through
translator): I became aware of
it through

20:47.379 --> 20:51.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my friends who got the shot
three days ago.
Since they're not having any
side effects,

20:51.183 --> 20:55.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I decided to come and have a go
at it myself,
because I feel it will protect
me.

20:55.187 --> 21:01.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Kanu works on a
team that buries
the highly contagious dead. He
has been shunned

21:01.060 --> 21:04.663 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by friends, even forced out of
his own home.

21:04.697 --> 21:08.267 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RICHARD KANU (through
translator): I will
go back and tell them that I
have had the

21:08.300 --> 21:11.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
vaccine and they should rest
assured that
I won't have the virus. I will
probably encourage

21:11.937 --> 21:13.739 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
them to step forward as well.

21:13.772 --> 21:20.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Bad traffic
delays Jusu's ride
to the hospital, but, when he
arrives, the

21:20.946 --> 21:27.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
vaccine isn't spoiled, and the
volunteers
are ready. The nursing team
doesn't waste

21:27.319 --> 21:31.390 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
any time prepping for the jabs.

21:31.423 --> 21:37.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Aruna Thorlie is a chlorine
sprayer who disinfects
Ebola treatment units.

21:37.863 --> 21:40.132 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Have you felt anything
different? Did it hurt,
anything?

21:40.166 --> 21:43.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARUNA THORLIE, Vaccine Trial
Volunteer (through
translator): I feel the same as
I did before.

21:43.335 --> 21:45.304 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I hope and pray that it works.

21:45.337 --> 21:50.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The vaccine is
made by Merck.
The trial is a partnership
between the Sierra

21:50.075 --> 21:55.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Leone Ministry of Health, the
U.S. Centers
for Disease Control and
Prevention and the

21:55.047 --> 21:56.849 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
medical college in Freetown.

21:56.882 --> 22:02.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. MOHAMED SAMAI: Once we can
document the
effectiveness of the vaccine,
and we are now

22:02.454 --> 22:07.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sure that it can really protect
them, we can
move to another stage, where we
will look

22:07.593 --> 22:10.563 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
at the community and the
population at large.

22:10.596 --> 22:16.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Across the border
in Liberia,
a separate trial is testing the
same vaccine,

22:16.902 --> 22:22.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
along with another one made by
GlaxoSmithKline.
It is open to all and based at
this hospital

22:22.875 --> 22:24.610 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Monrovia.

22:24.643 --> 22:29.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the darkest days of the
crisis here in
Liberia, a senior doctor and
nurse here at

22:29.315 --> 22:34.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Redemption Hospital contracted
Ebola virus
disease, and they subsequently
died. Many

22:35.020 --> 22:39.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the health care workers here
became afraid
to come to work and the hospital
had to close

22:39.892 --> 22:44.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
