a way to talk. But, right now,
they can't

27:19.037 --> 27:20.772 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
even talk.

27:20.806 --> 27:27.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. SUSAN COLLINS (R), Maine:
Does it make
sense that we require one case
of measles

27:27.212 --> 27:33.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be reported to a federal
government agency,
but not a cyber-attack?

27:34.019 --> 27:39.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But there are some
security advocates
and privacy groups who say the
law manages

27:39.892 --> 27:43.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to go too far and not quite far
enough.

27:43.328 --> 27:45.197 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has that debate.

27:45.230 --> 27:49.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: To understand
more, we're joined
by James Lewis, senior fellow
for the Center

27:49.234 --> 27:54.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for Strategic and International
Studies, and
Elissa Shevinsky, founder of
JeKuDo, a tech

27:55.007 --> 27:58.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
start-up designed to provide
private communications
to customers.

27:58.677 --> 28:00.279 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And welcome to both of you.

28:00.312 --> 28:02.147 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
James Lewis, let me start with
you.

28:02.180 --> 28:07.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The proponents of this in
Congress say that
this will allow the government
to coordinate

28:07.853 --> 28:11.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
information, and they think this
is the best
way to do it, and then push back
to other

28:11.957 --> 28:15.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
companies, push out information
about how
to prevent it in the future.

28:15.193 --> 28:17.496 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JAMES LEWIS, Center for
Strategic and International
Studies: You know, it's a really
good first

28:17.529 --> 28:23.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
step, and it's great that
Congress managed
to pass a law, almost amazing.

28:23.635 --> 28:31.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have a lot of work to do.
And in cyber-security
in general, this is a little
step. In information-sharing,

28:31.076 --> 28:35.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a lot of things have to come
together for
it to work. We have tried this
for a long

28:35.681 --> 28:41.887 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
time. It's hard to share
information, classified
information, private
information. We will

28:41.920 --> 28:45.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see where we are a year from
now, but a good
first step, a long way to go.

28:45.891 --> 28:50.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: From a security
perspective,
what's the goal here, and how
would the new

28:50.062 --> 28:51.797 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
law try to achieve it?

28:51.830 --> 28:56.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES LEWIS: This is something
the U.S. has
been trying to do for almost 18
years now,

28:56.168 --> 28:57.903 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and it's never worked.

28:57.936 --> 29:02.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The theory is that, if you
remove some of
the obstacles to sharing
information, people

29:02.908 --> 29:07.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will do more, will know what the
threats are,
and maybe they will take action.
But that's

29:07.846 --> 29:08.981 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
where the bill falls apart.

29:09.014 --> 29:10.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's where you
see a problem
on it?

29:10.449 --> 29:12.317 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JAMES LEWIS: Yes.

29:12.351 --> 29:16.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is no incentive for people
to use information.
This doesn't change -- it's like
me telling

29:16.421 --> 29:20.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you, hey, the Chinese are trying
to hack into
your computer, be ready. It
doesn't really

29:21.026 --> 29:26.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
affect what people are going to
do to defend
themselves. And it keeps us in a
reactive

29:26.598 --> 29:28.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
posture.

29:28.266 --> 29:32.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Elissa Shevinsky,
a lot of
people have raised privacy
concerns in all

29:32.170 --> 29:35.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this. You come at it from that
angle. Explain
the problems you see.

29:35.407 --> 29:37.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELISSA SHEVINSKY, Founder,
JeKuDo Privacy
Company: There are numerous
problems with

29:37.275 --> 29:39.144 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this bill.

29:39.177 --> 29:44.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It doesn't actually help us with
security.
Rather, it's more information
gathering for

29:44.983 --> 29:51.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
