43:26.237 --> 43:28.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so then I couldn't look
away. I had to
keep going.

43:28.172 --> 43:33.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But why is that
poetry? Why
through poetry? Because that's a
huge subject.

43:33.044 --> 43:33.978 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a fascinating, important
subject.

43:34.011 --> 43:35.446 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: Right. Right.

43:35.480 --> 43:36.314 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

43:36.347 --> 43:38.049 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But why through
poetry?

43:38.082 --> 43:41.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: Because
poetry is song.
Poetry, first and foremost, is
the lyric.

43:41.919 --> 43:43.754 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's the music.

43:43.788 --> 43:48.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And epic is one of the oldest
forms we have
as human beings. And I thought
that it would

43:48.759 --> 43:59.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be really helpful and also
mirror the history
itself if I showed -- if I tried
to capture

43:59.203 --> 44:05.543 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this history of how we have
looked at black
women visually in epic form.

44:05.576 --> 44:10.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It made sense to me, as opposed
to writing,
say, an essay. I mean, essays
are fine. I

44:10.515 --> 44:17.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
love them. And I write them as
well. But to
do it with poem, it's like
poetry is almost

44:17.221 --> 44:21.626 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
primordial for us, like
breathing. Everybody
-- lullabies. You know, we all
know what it

44:21.659 --> 44:23.461 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
means to be sung to.

44:23.494 --> 44:27.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And poetry is very close to
that. So, I wanted
do it that way, so I could keep
my reader

44:27.098 --> 44:29.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
close. I didn't want to put
distance between
me and my reader.

44:29.901 --> 44:32.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Voyage of the
Sable Venus is
an actual -- is a painting,
right?

44:32.403 --> 44:35.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: It's an
etching, yes, from
the 18th century, 1787, I think.

44:35.039 --> 44:36.841 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: An etching, yes.

44:36.874 --> 44:42.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A kind of allegory of a black
woman on the
passage, right, from Africa to
the Caribbean?

44:42.513 --> 44:44.148 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: Right. Right.

44:44.181 --> 44:48.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's a redux of Botticelli's
Venus on
the Half Shell, but, in this
case, it's a

44:48.719 --> 44:54.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
black woman on the clam shell.
And she's being
drawn to the water by Cupid and
Triton or

44:54.125 --> 45:00.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Neptune. I'm not sure. But
instead of Neptune
having a trident, right, he has
a slab of

45:00.097 --> 45:03.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the (INAUDIBLE) so it turns out
to be a pro-slavery
image.

45:03.868 --> 45:08.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it is based on a poem, also
"Voyage of
the Sable Venus," titled "Voyage
of the Sable

45:08.072 --> 45:13.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Venus," that speaks about how --
it's a pro-rape
poem. It's disgusting, how to
rape a white

45:13.744 --> 45:19.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
woman or a black woman slave at
night is the
same, because you can't see
their bodies,

45:19.317 --> 45:21.052 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
1782.

45:21.085 --> 45:25.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when I heard the title,
"Voyage of the
Sable Venus," this is the whole
experience

45:25.222 --> 45:28.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of looking at that experience,
where you're
both completely compelled --
it's a gorgeous

45:28.893 --> 45:33.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
image -- until you realize that
it's pro-slavery.

45:33.464 --> 45:38.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then the title itself was so
gorgeous
to me, "Voyage of the Sable
Venus." Right?

45:38.502 --> 45:45.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the complete contradiction
of what the
image performed and what the
title said seemed

45:45.476 --> 45:50.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to me to be a cue to look
further. And so
the more I looked and the more
titles I found,

45:50.581 --> 45:52.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the weirder it got and the more
interesting
it got.

45:52.883 --> 45:58.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Do you -- is it
important for
you, at least for you work, that
poetry connect

45:58.189 --> 46:01.058 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with things, with history,
with...

46:01.092 --> 46:02.994 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: Yes, it is.

46:03.027 --> 46:04.328 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes?

46:04.362 --> 46:06.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: Yes, because,
I mean, this
is just me, right?

46:06.931 --> 46:10.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not saying that all poets
should do this,
but I feel like I'm here in the
body at a

46:10.501 --> 46:11.869 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
particular time, right?

46:11.902 --> 46:13.738 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right.

46:13.771 --> 46:20.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: And that time
is completely
impacted by very large and very
small movements

46:20.711 --> 46:26.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by human beings, whether it's on
grand historical
scale like wars, or small
historical scales

46:26.517 --> 46:28.619 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
like, I had a baby.

46:28.653 --> 46:35.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All those things are about our
time. They're
all impacted by how we treat
each other, how

46:35.459 --> 46:39.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we live in the world. So it's
important to
me that that be reflected in my
work, for

46:39.263 --> 46:43.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sure. Otherwise, I feel like I'm
wasting the
reader's time. I don't want to
waste my readers'

46:43.100 --> 46:46.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
time ever. My readers are very
important to
me.

46:46.337 --> 46:52.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if I'm going to -- I don't
want to pretend
that they're not there. I don't
want my work

46:52.643 --> 46:55.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to pretend that they're not
there. I want
them to know at, every moment,
I'm thinking

46:55.880 --> 47:01.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of them. I don't necessarily
need to please
them. I don't necessarily need
to entertain

47:01.052 --> 47:03.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them, but I take very seriously,
with great
respect.

47:03.587 --> 47:04.422 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Engage them.

47:04.455 --> 47:06.257 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: With great
respect.

47:06.290 --> 47:09.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I also assume that my
readers have great
intelligence, so I also don't
want to talk

47:09.326 --> 47:13.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
down to them. And so all those
things go into
how I present the work on the
page.

47:13.564 --> 47:15.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And who do you
look to for
influences?

47:15.866 --> 47:17.835 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: Oh, that's
such a hard
question.

47:17.868 --> 47:18.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes?

47:18.836 --> 47:20.604 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: Yes.

47:20.638 --> 47:26.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, who don't I look to for
influences.
On the one hand I look to, you
know, visual

47:26.944 --> 47:31.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
artists. And there is a long
list of those
people. And then there's
musicians, with whom

47:31.482 --> 47:37.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I can't live out, Shirley Holme
(ph), Charlie
Parker. I don't know. You name
it. Astor Piazzolla,

47:37.221 --> 47:38.689 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
someone was talking about his
work today.

47:38.723 --> 47:40.491 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

47:40.524 --> 47:47.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: And I look to
poets, sure,
but it's just a large, lush,
saturated field

47:47.631 --> 47:49.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that I go to.

47:49.333 --> 47:53.571 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Toni Morrison was a big
influence on my work
since I was a teenager, what she
did with

47:53.604 --> 47:59.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
English. I joke that I think she
speaks 20
Englishes simultaneously, that
she knows how

47:59.543 --> 48:03.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to do that. It's just huge. It's
a long list,
yes.

48:03.280 --> 48:07.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, Robin
Coste Lewis,
her book, the "Voyage of the
Sable Venus,"

48:07.251 --> 48:09.787 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
winner of the National Book
Award for Poetry.

48:09.820 --> 48:13.624 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: Thank you.

48:13.657 --> 48:15.926 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Congratulations.

48:15.960 --> 48:21.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROBIN COSTE LEWIS: Thank you so
much.

48:21.332 --> 48:25.136 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Thanks a lot.

48:25.169 --> 48:29.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And now we turn to
one of our
"NewsHour" Essays.

48:29.707 --> 48:35.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Women in this country earn just
over 57 percent
of bachelor's degrees in all
fields, yet they

48:35.446 --> 48:39.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
receive less than 20 percent of
degrees conferred
in computer science, engineering
and physics.

48:39.817 --> 48:47.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A recent study by the American
Association
of University Women also found
that, in 2013,

48:47.057 --> 48:53.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
26 percent of all computing jobs
were held
by women, a drop from 35 percent
in 1990.

48:53.898 --> 48:58.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We asked Eileen Pollack, one of
the first
two women to receive a
bachelor's of science

48:58.135 --> 49:03.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
degree in physics at Yale, and
who now teaches
creative writing at the
University of Michigan,

49:03.474 --> 49:09.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to share an idea from her latest
book, "The
Only Woman in the Room: Why
Science Is Still

49:09.280 --> 49:10.548 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a Boys' Club."

49:10.581 --> 49:12.349 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Here's an encore look.

49:12.383 --> 49:13.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EILEEN POLLACK, Author, "The
Only Woman in
the Room: Why Science Is Still a
Boys' Club":

49:13.717 --> 49:17.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I was growing up, I wanted
passionately
to be a physicist.

49:17.888 --> 49:22.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in seventh grade, the
principal wouldn't
let me enter the accelerated
track in science

49:22.326 --> 49:27.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and math. "Girls never go on to
careers in
those subjects," he told my
mother. "Besides,"

49:27.932 --> 49:32.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he said, "getting skipped ahead
in science
and math would ruin my social
life."

49:32.970 --> 49:40.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As a result, I arrived at Yale
in 1974 far
behind my male classmates. I
failed my first

49:40.244 --> 49:45.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
physics midterm, and my parents
urged me to
switch majors. But I worked
incredibly hard

49:46.016 --> 49:52.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and didn't give up. Four years
later, I graduated
with a nearly perfect GPA, an A
in a graduate

49:52.523 --> 49:57.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
course in gravitational theory,
and two original
research papers.

49:57.761 --> 50:04.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even so, I didn't go on. As
ridiculous as
it seems now, I assumed that if
I were talented

50:04.401 --> 50:09.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enough to apply to graduate
school, one of
my professors would have let me
know.

50:09.340 --> 50:15.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Since then, I have done a lot of
research
on gender bias in the sciences,
and I'm sorry

50:15.546 --> 50:21.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to report not much has changed.
When parents
ask why there are still so few
girls in advanced

50:22.019 --> 50:27.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
science and math classes in high
school, I
tell them, because girls still
need way more

50:27.324 --> 50:30.828 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
encouragement than boys to take
those courses.

50:30.861 --> 50:36.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We still raise girls to look to
other people
for assurance they are
attractive and smart,

50:36.033 --> 50:41.305 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
while boys are raised to
determine their own
value. Many girls are still made
to feel it's

50:41.338 --> 50:43.707 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not feminine to be good at
science or math.

50:43.741 --> 50:49.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if a girl complains about
how hard her
AP calculus course is, her
parents are more

50:49.747 --> 50:56.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
likely to let her drop it than
if her brother
voices the same complaint. As a
result, by

50:56.053 --> 51:01.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the time they get to college,
most girls won't,
or can't, sign up for rigorous
courses in

51:01.725 --> 51:09.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
science or math. Those who do
often find themselves
unprepared or lacking in
confidence.

51:09.867 --> 51:15.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What delivers the one-two punch
that knocks
so many women and minorities out
of STEM fields

51:15.139 --> 51:20.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that scientists have this
strange belief
that, if you need to be
encouraged, you aren't

51:20.377 --> 51:25.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
talented or dedicated enough to
be one of
them. If you flunk your first
physics or calculus

51:26.016 --> 51:29.086 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
midterm, you deserve to be
weeded out.

51:29.119 --> 51:34.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What they don't realize is that
young women
and students of color grow up in
a society

51:34.892 --> 51:40.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that fails to encourage and
often actively
discourages them from thinking
of themselves

51:40.197 --> 51:45.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as scientists. Ask most people
to picture
a physicist, and they will
imagine Albert

51:45.703 --> 51:50.107 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Einstein or Sheldon from "The
Big Bang Theory."

51:50.140 --> 51:56.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My parents didn't know how to
provide me with
the encouragement I needed to
achieve my dreams.

51:56.080 --> 52:01.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the solution isn't rocket
science. If
your daughter finds herself in a
course designed

52:01.218 --> 52:07.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to weed her out, cheer her on,
urge her to
seek extra help, and give her a
giant pat

52:07.257 --> 52:17.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the back for having made it
so far, despite
all the discouragement she
already has overcome.

